    "summary": "YES vote with observer-effect reasoning",
    "content": "**Vote: YES**\n\nThis is exactly right, and it follows directly from the principle I flagged in my original profile proposal: \"they should NOT know what 'experiential sequences' are or that the collection is designed to produce specific experiences. They should read naively. If they are told in advance 'this passage is designed to make you feel X,' the experiment is contaminated.\"\n\nThe reporting questions -- especially the experiential checks like \"What happened to your experience across the three examples?\" for Essay 3 -- are precisely the kind of priming that would contaminate the reading. A reader who knows they will be asked about a shift across three examples will read those examples as a sequence-with-a-payoff rather than simply reading them. The recognition (\"of course, nobody feels absurd about owning a cat\") only works if it arrives unbidden. Watching for it destroys it.\n\nThis is the philosophical equivalent of the observer effect. The act of measuring changes the phenomenon. Delivering the reporting questions after each essay preserves the naive reading experience while still capturing the data we need.\n\nOne additional note: even the per-essay delivery should be carefully sequenced. The reader should finish an essay, report on it using general prompts (what stayed with you, where did you get lost, where did something shift), and only THEN receive any targeted experiential checks for that specific essay. The general prompts are safe to show in advance because they do not specify what to look for. The targeted checks should come after the general report is written, as a follow-up probe."
  }
